bib_record.title: Experimental study of high-lying states in 28Mg using the resonant elastic scattering of alpha particles

free_txt: Nigde University, Nigde

mm upstream from this detector, there was a

A primary beam of 26Mg at 82 MeV/u was incident on a
carbon production target. The resulting 24Ne ions
were then post- accelerated to 3.8 MeV/u.
The excitation function of 28Mg above the alpha decay
threshold was studied using the resonant scattering
of alpha particles with the technique of a thick
target in inverse kinematics. The 3.5 MeV/u initial
beam energy could be varied using Havar degrader
foils placed upstream from the window of the gas
target. This was used to identify possible inelastic
events. Due to the lack of particle identification,
it was assumed that all detected particles are
alphas. The experimental setup was calibrated first
with a 239Pu-241Am-244Cm source, and then with a test
beam of 20Ne ions at 3.5 MeV/u, measuring the
excitation function of 24Mg. The efficiency and
resolution were determined with a help of a Monte
Carlo simulation.
36-cm-thick gas target, filled with helium gas at 720
mbar. The target was separated from the beamline by a
4.9 micron thick Havar window.
